overview: >-
  The conversation began with a user's urgent request to fix numerous issues in
  a pull request, emphasizing broken Vercel deployments and critical security
  concerns. The agent started by systematically gathering information from PR
  comments, CI checks, and code files. Initial fixes addressed lint errors,
  security vulnerabilities like trivially forgeable admin cookies (migrating to
  HMAC-based sessions using Web Crypto API for Edge Runtime compatibility), and
  various bugs related to PDF generation, number input handling, and UI
  functionality. Pagination limits were also introduced for API routes and CSV
  exports to prevent resource exhaustion.

  A major pivot occurred when Vercel deployments continued to fail despite local
  builds passing. This led to the discovery and resolution of several critical
  issues: a missing  in the Prisma schema, a severe Next.js
  security vulnerability (CVE-2025-66478) requiring an upgrade to Next.js
  16.1.1, and subsequent breaking changes in Next.js 16 that necessitated
  migrating ESLint from  to a direct ESLint flat configuration.
  Finally, a build-time error on Vercel related to Prisma client initialization
  was resolved by implementing lazy-loading for the Prisma client. The e2e tests
  were also updated to reflect current application content. The conversation
  concluded with all GitHub Actions and Vercel deployments successfully passing,
  and a minor fix to the questionnaire's progress bar logic to show 0% on the
  initial step.
